Many a true word is spoken in jest.
Least said, soonest mended.
Fools rush in where angels fear to tread.
Make not your mouth your purse.
Set a thief to catch a thief.
Soft fire makes sweet malt.
Give the devil his due.
Fair words butter no parsnips.
Hunger breaks stone walls.
Little strokes fell great oaks.
As you make your bed, so must you lie in it.
Ill gotten gains never prosper.
A stitch in time saves nine.
Still waters run deep.
The pitcher goes often to the well, but is broken at last.
Barking dogs seldom bite.
Spare at the spigot, spoil at the bung.
Where ignorance is bliss, tis folly to be wise.
Great boast, small roast.
The proof of the pudding is in the eating.
Haste makes waste.
He who sups with the devil should have a long spoon.
Many hands make light work.
Out of the frying pan into the fire.
The cat may look at a king.
One swallow makes not a summer.
Set a beggar on horseback and hell ride to the devil.
Whats bred in the bone will come out in the flesh.
A watched pot never boils.
The cart before the horse.
Every dog has his day.
Let sleeping dogs lie.
The more haste, the less speed.
Too many cooks spoil the broth.
Give him an inch and hell take an ell.
Truth will out.
When the cats away, the mice will play.
One good turn deserves another.
Theres many a slip twixt cup and lip.
The shoemakers son always goes barefoot.
Little said is soon amended.
You cannot serve God and Mammon.
Call a spade a spade.
A rolling stone gathers no moss.
Keep your powder dry.
Nothing venture, nothing have.
Pride will have a fall.
Faint heart never won fair lady.
Old sins cast long shadows.
Give a man rope enough and hell hang himself.
A fair face may hide a foul heart.
Dead men tell no tales.
The longest day must have an end.
A friend to all is a friend to none.
Where theres smoke, theres fire.
The more you stir it, the worse it stinks.
Half a loaf is better than no bread.
As good be hanged for a sheep as for a lamb.
The early bird catches the worm.
The tail wagging the dog.
The cobbler should stick to his last.
A bird in the hand is worth two in the bush.
Better the devil you know than the devil you dont.
No penny, no paternoster.
Fair exchange is no robbery.
It takes two to make a quarrel.
Small rain lays great dust.
The weakest goes to the wall.
Hunger is the best sauce.
He who laughs last, laughs longest.
When poverty comes in at the door, love flies out at the window.
Better to bend than break.
Where theres a will, theres a way.
Much cry and little wool.
Old birds are not caught with chaff.
The more the merrier.
A nods as good as a wink to a blind horse.
Time and tide wait for no man.
The pot calls the kettle black.
Many a mickle makes a muckle.
You cannot make bricks without straw.
What the eye sees not, the heart grieves not.
A fools bolt is soon shot.
One law for the rich and another for the poor.
Ill winds blow nobody good.
Good counsel has no price.
The mill cannot grind with the water that is past.
He who will not work shall not eat.
Old soldiers never die, they only fade away.
The devil finds work for idle hands.
Much ado about nothing.
Forewarned is forearmed.
The end crowns the work.
All is fish that comes to net.
Better safe than sorry.
Little learning is a dangerous thing.
Needs must when the devil drives.
A still tongue makes a wise head.
What cannot be cured must be endured.
He who pays the piper calls the tune.